body: "## Source\nGitHub issue #489 (dogfood, version 2026.7.9).\n\n## Reproduction\n```bash\npm init uxt --defaults --author probe\npm create task \"First\"                       # -> uxt-A (open)\npm create task \"Second\" --blocked-by uxt-A   # -> uxt-B (status: blocked)\npm next\n```\n`pm next` emits `summary.blocked: 0` and no blocked-companion section, while the same envelope's recommended entry says `unblocks 1 item(s): uxt-B` and `pm list-blocked` correctly shows 1 blocked item. A `blocked_limit: 5` filter is even printed, so the companion surface is advertised but never populated.\n\n## Expected\n`summary.blocked` counts blocked items and the blocked companion lists them with their blockers (as `pm next --help` documents).\n\n## Why it matters for agents\n`pm next` is the primary \"what should I work on\" entrypoint. The envelope contradicts itself (unblocks list vs blocked: 0), so an agent trusting the summary concludes no blocked work exists and skips triage. The data is already computed for the unblocks reasons — only the summary/companion aggregation misses it.\n\n## Scope\nFix the aggregation in the pm next summary + blocked companion; add a regression test covering the blocked-companion path in a fresh workspace. Related output-shape defects: pm-hfg5 (ready[0] duplication), pm-yl6c (cross-agent resume recommendation)."
